ship of Class B shares, will be able to elect all the Class B Directors. Furthermore, because he will also hold a majority of the combined voting power of Class A and Class B stock, he will be able to elect the Common Stock Directors as well, giving him the power to control the election of the entire board.\n\n*   **Removal Procedures:**\n    *   **Class B Directors:** Can be removed with or without cause by the affirmative vote of the holders of at least a majority of the voting power of the outstanding Class B common stock, voting separately as a class.\n    *   **Common Stock Directors:** Can be removed with or without cause by the affirmative vote of the holders of at least a majority of the voting power of the outstanding voting common stock (Class A and B), voting together as a single class.\n\n*   **Vacancy Filling:**\n    *   **Class B Director Vacancies:** May be filled by the affirmative vote of the holders of at least a majority of the voting power of the outstanding Class B common stock, voting separately as a class, **or** by the remaining Class B Directors, and not by any other persons.\n    *   **Common Stock Director Vacancies:** May be filled by the affirmative vote of the holders of at least a majority of the voting power of the outstanding voting common stock, voting together as a single class, **or** by the remaining directors.\n\n*   **Special Leadership Protections:** The charter provides a special voting right specifically for Elon Musk's leadership roles. His removal from the board and from his positions as **Chief Executive Officer and Chairman of the board** requires the approval of the holders of at least a majority of the voting power of the outstanding Class B common stock, voting separately as a class.\n\n*   **Other Class B Voting Rights:** Beyond director elections, the approval of the Class B common stock, voting separately as a class, is required for any amendment to the charter that would change the rights, powers, preferences, and