s."\n\n### 3. Concentrated Voting Power\nThe documents detail how Elon Musk\'s control over a majority of Class B shares gives him decisive power over all matters requiring shareholder approval, limiting Class A shareholders\' influence.\n\n*   **Control Over All Directors:** The text states that because Mr. Musk will beneficially own a majority of the voting power, he "will be able to elect all the members of our board." This includes the "Common Stock Directors," who are nominally elected by all shareholders voting together but are effectively controlled by his majority vote.\n*   **Control Over Corporate Matters:** Mr. Musk’s concentrated voting power allows him to "control the outcome of matters requiring shareholder approval," which may "have the effect of deferring, delaying or discouraging hostile takeovers, or changes in control or management, of the Company."\n*   **Long-Term Control:** The structure is designed to perpetuate this control. The conversion mechanism for Class B shares will, over time, "increas[e] the relative voting power of those holders of Class B common stock who retain their shares."\n*   **Risk of Control Shifts:** A specific risk is disclosed that if Mr. Musk sells enough Class B shares to lose his majority of that class, "another holder or group of holders of Class B common stock could obtain the ability to elect and remove a majority of our board and thereby effectively control the Company," leading to changes that "may not be aligned with the interests of holders of our Class A common stock."\n*   **Charter Opt-Outs:** The company\'s charter opts out of separate class votes under Texas law for matters like increasing authorized shares or reclassifications, further entrenching the power of the controlling shareholder.',
